goals.description: Lower my blood pressure to my goal
Exercise or be more physically active
Lower my hemoglobin A1C to goal set by provider
Follow fluid restrictions set by my provider

carePlans.last_vist_notes:
Patient Visit Summary
1. Date of Visit

November 13, 2025

2. Consulting Doctor

Dr. Stephen Kemnele

3. General Diagnosis / Past Relevant History (One-Liner)

Patient with long-standing Hypertension and Chronic Kidney Disease (Stage 3), generally stable on current treatment but requiring ongoing monitoring.

4. Chief Complaint

Patient reports mild morning headaches and occasional ankle swelling over the past week.

5. Objective Findings
5.1 Vitals

(Most readings entered by clinician)

BP: 137/77 mmHg

HR: 73 bpm

RR: 16 breaths/min

Temp: 98.1°F (36.7°C)

Weight: 176 lbs (79.8 kg)

BMI: 27.4 kg/m²

5.2 Physical Exam Findings

Appears well, no acute distress

Lungs clear, no wheezing or crackles

Heart regular rate and rhythm

Mild bilateral ankle edema (+1)

No jugular venous distention

Abdomen soft, non-tender

No focal neurological deficits

5.3 Labs or Imaging (New or Trending Data)


Creatinine: 1.6 mg/dL (slightly increased from 1.5)

eGFR: 42 mL/min (stable)

HbA1c: 7.4% (mildly elevated; prior was 7.2%)

Potassium: 4.9 mEq/L (normal)

Hemoglobin: 12.4 g/dL (mild anemia; stable)

Urine protein/creatinine ratio: 0.6 (elevated but unchanged)

6. Plan of Care
6a. Medications

New Prescriptions:

Amlodipine 5 mg PO daily — for improved BP control

Ferrous sulfate 325 mg PO daily — for CKD-related anemia

Dosage Changes:

Lisinopril increased from 10 mg to 20 mg daily — for BP and proteinuria management

Discontinued Medications:

Hydrochlorothiazide 12.5 mg — discontinued due to CKD progression and ankle swelling

6b. Lifestyle Guidance

Limit sodium to <2 grams/day

Continue daily walking 20–30 minutes as tolerated

Limit processed foods and follow kidney-friendly diet (moderate protein, avoid high-phosphorus sodas, limit bananas/oranges)

Maintain fluid intake as directed by provider (no excess fluids)

Elevate legs when sitting to reduce ankle swelling

Continue home BP monitoring and log readings twice daily

Avoid NSAIDs (ibuprofen, naproxen) due to CKD

6c. Labs / Tests Ordered


BMP (Basic Metabolic Panel): to monitor kidney function and electrolytes

CBC: to evaluate anemia and fatigue

Urine Protein/Creatinine Ratio: to assess CKD progression

HbA1c: to monitor glucose control trends

Renal Ultrasound: to evaluate kidney structure and baseline for CKD management

6d. Referrals

Nephrology referral — CKD stage 3 with worsening creatinine

Dietitian referral — guidance for low-sodium and renal diet

6e. Follow-Up

Follow-up in 4 weeks for BP review and lab results.

7. Patient Instructions (Plain Language)

Take all medications every day exactly as prescribed.

Check your blood pressure twice daily and record your numbers.

Reduce salt in your diet and avoid packaged/processed foods.

Drink only the amount of fluids recommended by your provider.

Walk for at least 20–30 minutes each day if you can.

Elevate your feet when resting to help with swelling.

Avoid pain medications like ibuprofen or naproxen unless cleared by your doctor.

Call your doctor right away if you experience:

Chest pain

Severe headache or very high BP (>180 systolic)

Trouble breathing

Sudden swelling of legs or face

Dizziness or fainting

Go to the ER if symptoms are severe or sudden.

8. Next Visit Date

January 10, 2026 at 10:00 AM
